</li><li class="postbit blockbody" id="post_11">
	<div class="header">
		<div class="datetime">August 3rd, 2013, 04:29 PM</div>
		<span class="username">Ikeya</span>
	</div>
	
	
		<div class="title">Re: For the Sys Admins and Tech Ops folks...</div>
	
	<div class="content">
		<blockquote class="restore">So, update.<br />
<br />
We had originally wanted to get operations on board with us before going to the upper management to present a unified front.  Since this would be a radical significant departure from the current corporate mandate (Can only deploy after midnight EST on Fridays), we wanted pretty much all technology fronts on board with this being a preferably idea to do the sale to management.<br />
<br />
We had the meeting.  They expressed similar frustrations that there's a mad rush for every application to deploy in the same time window and want to shuffle them around.  They also don't like how time consuming it is and how difficult it is to fix deploys when something inevitably goes wrong mid way through.  Unfortunately, they're not quite on board yet with more frequent deployments and want to get automated deployments in place across the board.  Which isn't a bad thing and definitely something that needs to (and probably should have already) happen.</blockquote>
	</div>
</li><li class="postbit blockbody" id="post_12">
	<div class="header">
		<div class="datetime">August 4th, 2013, 09:19 AM</div>
		<span class="username">Goladus</span>
	</div>
	
	
		<div class="title">Re: For the Sys Admins and Tech Ops folks...</div>
	
	<div class="content">
		<blockquote class="restore">Quick answer to this one:<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			What would I, as a member of the development team, have to convince you to let us touch production more regularly?
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div>If this is a public company subject to Sarbanes-Oxley audits and the production system affects financial reporting: it may be neigh-impossible short of getting laws changed.  If SOX compliance is a big deal for your company the separation of duties policies may be there explicitly to clarify chains of accountability-- often explicitly preventing software developers from having any write-access at all to production systems.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			<div>
				Originally Posted by <strong>Ikeya</strong>
				<a href="showthread.php?p=1788452#post1788452" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost.gif" alt="View Post" /></a>
			</div>
			<div class="message">...How can I convince you let me deploy to production servers more regularly?  Team is facing an issue where we're only allowed to deploy at most once every 3 months.  This tends to be a time consuming and tedious process that takes up most of the night and the following morning.  We'd like to be able to knock the time between deployments down (ideally moving towards a Continuous Deployment or Delivery model, but that's a way off).</div>
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div>Generally speaking, operations first priority is keeping the engines running.  If you have a web application that generates revenue for the company, downtime translates pretty directly into lost revenue.  From an ops perspective, release cycles and change controls are in place to reduce costly downtime (or the risk of it).  They're also in place to help ensure accountability rests with people of the right pay grade and that institutional ops knowledge is preserved as much as possible.<br />
<br />
Why is the deployment process so long and tedious?  Where is the bottleneck?  Where is there bloat?  How much downtime is required for a particular change?  <br />
<br />
Are there other cost reasons why it is the way it is?  What's preventing an A/B deployment model or something similar?  <br />
<br />
How stable does the application tend to be after a release?  How often have developers introduced bugs that cause webservers to crash nightly at 2:00 AM, requiring the admins to wake up and restart the services?  If devs have a reputation for forgetting to turn off debug flags or allowing other crap into production then there may be a lot of extra QA and review processes required to certify the code into production.  Because in some cases, even when it was bad code that caused the site to go down and impact revenue, the downtime still counts against Operations uptime SLAs.</blockquote>
	</div>
</li><li class="postbit blockbody" id="post_13">
	<div class="header">
		<div class="datetime">August 4th, 2013, 09:26 AM</div>
		<span class="username">Goladus</span>
	</div>
	
	
		<div class="title">Re: For the Sys Admins and Tech Ops folks...</div>
	
	<div class="content">
		<blockquote class="restore"><div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			<div>
				Originally Posted by <strong>Ikeya</strong>
				<a href="showthread.php?p=1789127#post1789127" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost.gif" alt="View Post" /></a>
			</div>
			<div class="message">So, update.<br />
<br />
We had originally wanted to get operations on board with us before going to the upper management to present a unified front.  Since this would be a radical significant departure from the current corporate mandate (Can only deploy after midnight EST on Fridays), we wanted pretty much all technology fronts on board with this being a preferably idea to do the sale to management.<br />
<br />
We had the meeting.  They expressed similar frustrations that there's a mad rush for every application to deploy in the same time window and want to shuffle them around.  They also don't like how time consuming it is and how difficult it is to fix deploys when something inevitably goes wrong mid way through.  Unfortunately, they're not quite on board yet with more frequent deployments and want to get automated deployments in place across the board.  Which isn't a bad thing and definitely something that needs to (and probably should have already) happen.</div>
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div>One avenue may be to come up with some distinct deployment categories.<br />
<br />
For example, code updates that do not require a database schema change might incur far less risk.  You might be able to have a weekly morning maintenance window for those changes.  Especially if those are the easiest portion for the operations team to automate.  Ruthlessly cut any changes that don't belong in that window.</blockquote>
	</div>
